{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778981696787,"sessionID":"ses_1cc6e9e73ffe2HfOe2xPGj0ykX","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_YPCvy3fek0peUpIjxS6pE8Bl","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/__w/eval-ont-agent-go/eval-ont-agent-go/references_cache/PMID_8321236.md","offset":1,"limit":220},"output":"<path>/__w/eval-ont-agent-go/eval-ont-agent-go/references_cache/PMID_8321236.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: reference_id: PMID:8321236\n3: title: The fission yeast ferric reductase gene frp1+ is required for ferric iron uptake and encodes a protein that is homologous to the gp91-phox subunit of the human NADPH phagocyte oxidoreductase.\n4: authors:\n5: - Roman DG\n6: - Dancis A\n7: - Anderson GJ\n8: - Klausner RD\n9: journal: Mol Cell Biol\n10: year: '1993'\n11: doi: 10.1128/mcb.13.7.4342-4350.1993\n12: keywords:\n13: - Alleles\n14: - Amino Acid Sequence\n15: - Animals\n16: - Base Sequence\n17: - Cattle\n18: - \"Cloning, Molecular\"\n19: - \"DNA, Fungal/isolation & purification\"\n20: - FMN Reductase\n21: - Ferric Compounds/metabolism\n22: - Ferrous Compounds/metabolism\n23: - \"Gene Expression Regulation, Fungal\"\n24: - Genetic Complementation Test\n25: - Humans\n26: - Molecular Sequence Data\n27: - Mutation\n28: - \"NADH, NADPH Oxidoreductases/chemistry, genetics, metabolism\"\n29: - Phagocytes/enzymology\n30: - \"Promoter Regions, Genetic\"\n31: - Restriction Mapping\n32: - \"Schizosaccharomyces/enzymology, genetics, growth & development\"\n33: - Sequence Homology\n34: - Substrate Specificity\n35: - \"Transcription, Genetic\"\n36: content_type: abstract_only\n37: ---\n38: \n39: # The fission yeast ferric reductase gene frp1+ is required for ferric iron uptake and encodes a protein that is homologous to the gp91-phox subunit of the human NADPH phagocyte oxidoreductase.\n40: **Authors:** Roman DG, Dancis A, Anderson GJ, Klausner RD\n41: **Journal:** Mol Cell Biol (1993)\n42: **DOI:** [10.1128/mcb.13.7.4342-4350.1993](https://doi.org/10.1128/mcb.13.7.4342-4350.1993)\n43: \n44: ## Content\n45: \n46: 1. Mol Cell Biol. 1993 Jul;13(7):4342-50. doi: 10.1128/mcb.13.7.4342-4350.1993.\n47: \n48: The fission yeast ferric reductase gene frp1+ is required for ferric iron uptake \n49: and encodes a protein that is homologous to the gp91-phox subunit of the human \n50: NADPH phagocyte oxidoreductase.\n51: \n52: Roman DG(1), Dancis A, Anderson GJ, Klausner RD.\n53: \n54: Author information:\n55: (1)Cell Biology and Metabolism Branch, National Institute of Child Health and \n56: Human Development, Bethesda, Maryland 20892.\n57: \n58: We have identified a cell surface ferric reductase activity in the fission yeast \n59: Schizosaccharomyces pombe. A mutant strain deficient in this activity was also \n60: deficient in ferric iron uptake, while ferrous iron uptake was not impaired. \n61: Therefore, reduction is a required step in cellular ferric iron acquisition. We \n62: have cloned frp1+, the wild-type allele of the mutant gene. frp1+ mRNA levels \n63: were repressed by iron addition to the growth medium. Fusion of 138 nucleotides \n64: of frp1+ promoter sequences to a reporter gene, the bacterial chloramphenicol \n65: acetyltransferase gene, conferred iron-dependent regulation upon the latter when \n66: introduced into S. pombe. The predicted amino acid sequence of the frp1+ gene \n67: exhibits hydrophobic regions compatible with transmembrane domains. It shows \n68: similarity to the Saccharomyces cerevisiae FRE1 gene product and the gp91-phox \n69: protein, a component of the human NADPH phagocyte oxidoreductase that is \n70: deficient in X-linked chronic granulomatous disease.\n71: \n72: DOI: 10.1128/mcb.13.7.4342-4350.1993\n73: PMCID: PMC359993\n74: PMID: 8321236 [Indexed for MEDLINE]\n\n(End of file - total 74 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\nreference_id: PMID:8321236\ntitle: The fission yeast ferric reductase gene frp1+ is required for ferric iron uptake and encodes a protein that is homologous to the gp91-phox subunit of the human NADPH phagocyte oxidoreductase.\nauthors:\n- Roman DG\n- Dancis A\n- Anderson GJ\n- Klausner RD\njournal: Mol Cell Biol\nyear: '1993'\ndoi: 10.1128/mcb.13.7.4342-4350.1993\nkeywords:\n- Alleles\n- Amino Acid Sequence\n- Animals\n- Base Sequence\n- Cattle\n- \"Cloning, Molecular\"\n- \"DNA, Fungal/isolation & purification\"\n- FMN Reductase","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"references_cache/PMID_8321236.md","time":{"start":1778981696738,"end":1778981696773}},"id":"prt_e339274d5001HoOHFpne8pPGwE","sessionID":"ses_1cc6e9e73ffe2HfOe2xPGj0ykX","messageID":"msg_e33923907001CGGSkNjnuenN33"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778981696787,"sessionID":"ses_1cc6e9e73ffe2HfOe2xPGj0ykX","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_yCUWZA4ce7Avp4bamh135oxJ","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/__w/eval-ont-agent-go/eval-ont-agent-go/references_cache/PMID_39940646.md","offset":1,"limit":220},"output":"<path>/__w/eval-ont-agent-go/eval-ont-agent-go/references_cache/PMID_39940646.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: reference_id: PMID:39940646\n3: title: \"The Ferroxidase-Permease System for Transport of Iron Across Membranes: From Yeast to Humans.\"\n4: authors:\n5: - Amadei M\n6: - Polticelli F\n7: - Musci G\n8: - Bonaccorsi di Patti MC\n9: journal: Int J Mol Sci\n10: year: '2025'\n11: doi: 10.3390/ijms26030875\n12: keywords:\n13: - \"Ceruloplasmin/metabolism, chemistry\"\n14: - Humans\n15: - Iron/metabolism\n16: - Biological Transport\n17: - \"Membrane Transport Proteins/metabolism, chemistry\"\n18: - Cell Membrane/metabolism\n19: - Animals\n20: - Saccharomyces cerevisiae/metabolism\n21: - Yeasts/metabolism\n22: content_type: abstract_only\n23: ---\n24: \n25: # The Ferroxidase-Permease System for Transport of Iron Across Membranes: From Yeast to Humans.\n26: **Authors:** Amadei M, Polticelli F, Musci G, Bonaccorsi di Patti MC\n27: **Journal:** Int J Mol Sci (2025)\n28: **DOI:** [10.3390/ijms26030875](https://doi.org/10.3390/ijms26030875)\n29: \n30: ## Content\n31: \n32: 1. Int J Mol Sci. 2025 Jan 21;26(3):875. doi: 10.3390/ijms26030875.\n33: \n34: The Ferroxidase-Permease System for Transport of Iron Across Membranes: From \n35: Yeast to Humans.\n36: \n37: Amadei M(1), Polticelli F(2), Musci G(3), Bonaccorsi di Patti MC(1).\n38: \n39: Author information:\n40: (1)Department of Biochemical Sciences 'A. Rossi Fanelli', Sapienza University of \n41: Rome, 00185 Rome, Italy.\n42: (2)Department of Sciences, University Roma Tre, 00146 Rome, Italy.\n43: (3)Department of Biosciences and Territory, University of Molise, 86090 Pesche, \n44: Italy.\n45: \n46: Transport of iron across the cell membrane is a tightly controlled process \n47: carried out by specific proteins in all living cells. In yeast and in mammals, a \n48: system formed by an enzyme with ferroxidase activity coupled to a membrane \n49: transporter supports iron uptake or iron efflux, respectively. Ferroxidase \n50: belongs to the family of blue multicopper oxidases, enzymes able to couple the \n51: one-electron oxidation of substrate(s) to full reduction of molecular oxygen to \n52: water. On the other hand, the permeases are widely different and are specific to \n53: Fe3+ and Fe2+ in yeast and multicellular organisms, respectively. This review \n54: will describe the yeast and human ferroxidase-permease systems, highlighting \n55: similarities and differences in structure, function and regulation of the \n56: respective protein components.\n57: \n58: DOI: 10.3390/ijms26030875\n59: PMCID: PMC11817551\n60: PMID: 39940646 [Indexed for MEDLINE]\n61: \n62: Conflict of interest statement: The authors declare no conflict of interest.\n\n(End of file - total 62 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\nreference_id: PMID:39940646\ntitle: \"The Ferroxidase-Permease System for Transport of Iron Across Membranes: From Yeast to Humans.\"\nauthors:\n- Amadei M\n- Polticelli F\n- Musci G\n- Bonaccorsi di Patti MC\njournal: Int J Mol Sci\nyear: '2025'\ndoi: 10.3390/ijms26030875\nkeywords:\n- \"Ceruloplasmin/metabolism, chemistry\"\n- Humans\n- Iron/metabolism\n- Biological Transport\n- \"Membrane Transport Proteins/metabolism, chemistry\"\n- Cell Membrane/metabolism\n- Animals\n- Saccharomyces cerevisiae/metabolism","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"references_cache/PMID_39940646.md","time":{"start":1778981696756,"end":1778981696777}},"id":"prt_e339274ee00179DqUrt8b2qtSo","sessionID":"ses_1cc6e9e73ffe2HfOe2xPGj0ykX","messageID":"msg_e33923907001CGGSkNjnuenN33"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778981696787,"sessionID":"ses_1cc6e9e73ffe2HfOe2xPGj0ykX","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_ULZNE3ix1MgSPHt5wt4rVfzD","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/__w/eval-ont-agent-go/eval-ont-agent-go/references_cache/PMID_34614242.md","offset":1,"limit":220},"output":"<path>/__w/eval-ont-agent-go/eval-ont-agent-go/references_cache/PMID_34614242.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: reference_id: PMID:34614242\n3: title: Fission yeast RNA-binding proteins Puf2 and Puf4 are involved in repression of ferrireductase Frp1 expression in response to iron.\n4: authors:\n5: - Beaudoin J\n6: - Normant V\n7: - Brault A\n8: - Henry DJ\n9: - Bachand F\n10: - Massé É\n11: - Chua G\n12: - Labbé S\n13: journal: Mol Microbiol\n14: year: '2021'\n15: doi: 10.1111/mmi.14829\n16: keywords:\n17: - \"3' Untranslated Regions\"\n18: - \"DNA, Fungal\"\n19: - \"FMN Reductase/genetics, metabolism\"\n20: - \"Gene Expression Regulation, Fungal\"\n21: - Iron/metabolism\n22: - Mutation\n23: - \"Promoter Regions, Genetic\"\n24: - \"RNA Processing, Post-Transcriptional\"\n25: - \"RNA, Messenger/metabolism\"\n26: - \"RNA-Binding Proteins/genetics, metabolism\"\n27: - \"Schizosaccharomyces/genetics, metabolism\"\n28: - \"Schizosaccharomyces pombe Proteins/genetics, metabolism\"\n29: content_type: abstract_only\n30: ---\n31: \n32: # Fission yeast RNA-binding proteins Puf2 and Puf4 are involved in repression of ferrireductase Frp1 expression in response to iron.\n33: **Authors:** Beaudoin J, Normant V, Brault A, Henry DJ, Bachand F, Massé É, Chua G, Labbé S\n34: **Journal:** Mol Microbiol (2021)\n35: **DOI:** [10.1111/mmi.14829](https://doi.org/10.1111/mmi.14829)\n36: \n37: ## Content\n38: \n39: 1. Mol Microbiol. 2021 Nov;116(5):1361-1377. doi: 10.1111/mmi.14829. Epub 2021\n40: Oct  21.\n41: \n42: Fission yeast RNA-binding proteins Puf2 and Puf4 are involved in repression of \n43: ferrireductase Frp1 expression in response to iron.\n44: \n45: Beaudoin J(1), Normant V(1), Brault A(1), Henry DJ(2), Bachand F(1), Massé É(1), \n46: Chua G(2), Labbé S(1).\n47: \n48: Author information:\n49: (1)Département de Biochimie et de Génomique Fonctionnelle, Faculté de médecine \n50: et des sciences de la santé, Université de Sherbrooke, Sherbrooke, Quebec, \n51: Canada.\n52: (2)Biological Sciences, Integrative Cell Biology, University of Calgary, \n53: Calgary, Alberta, Canada.\n54: \n55: This study identifies a post-transcriptional mechanism of iron uptake regulation \n56: by Puf2 and Puf4 of the Pumilio and FBF (Puf) family of RNA-binding proteins in \n57: Schizosaccharomyces pombe. Cells expressing Puf2 and Puf4 stimulate decay of the \n58: frp1+ mRNA encoding a key enzyme of the reductive iron uptake pathway. Results \n59: consistently showed that frp1+ mRNA is stabilized in puf2Δ puf4Δ mutant cells \n60: under iron-replete conditions. As a result, puf2Δ puf4Δ cells exhibit an \n61: increased sensitivity to iron accompanied by enhanced ferrireductase activity. A \n62: pool of GFP-frp1+ 3'UTR RNAs was generated using a reporter gene containing the \n63: 3' untranslated region (UTR) of frp1+ that was under the control of a \n64: regulatable promoter. Results showed that Puf2 and Puf4 accelerate the \n65: destabilization of mRNAs containing the frp1+ 3'UTR which harbors two Pumilio \n66: response elements (PREs). Binding studies revealed that the PUM-homology \n67: RNA-binding domain of Puf2 and Puf4 expressed in Escherichia coli specifically \n68: interacts with PREs in the frp1+ 3'UTR. Using RNA immunoprecipitation in \n69: combination with reverse transcription qPCR assays, results showed that Puf2 and \n70: Puf4 interact preferentially with frp1+ mRNA under basal and iron-replete \n71: conditions, thereby contributing to inhibit Frp1 production and protecting cells \n72: against toxic levels of iron.\n73: \n74: © 2021 John Wiley & Sons Ltd.\n75: \n76: DOI: 10.1111/mmi.14829\n77: PMID: 34614242 [Indexed for MEDLINE]\n\n(End of file - total 77 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\nreference_id: PMID:34614242\ntitle: Fission yeast RNA-binding proteins Puf2 and Puf4 are involved in repression of ferrireductase Frp1 expression in response to iron.\nauthors:\n- Beaudoin J\n- Normant V\n- Brault A\n- Henry DJ\n- Bachand F\n- Massé É\n- Chua G\n- Labbé S\njournal: Mol Microbiol\nyear: '2021'\ndoi: 10.1111/mmi.14829\nkeywords:\n- \"3' Untranslated Regions\"\n- \"DNA, Fungal\"\n- \"FMN Reductase/genetics, metabolism\"\n- \"Gene Expression Regulation, Fungal\"","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"references_cache/PMID_34614242.md","time":{"start":1778981696762,"end":1778981696781}},"id":"prt_e339274f7001wFVjZHoLUmQhmH","sessionID":"ses_1cc6e9e73ffe2HfOe2xPGj0ykX","messageID":"msg_e33923907001CGGSkNjnuenN33"}}
