{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778982000413,"sessionID":"ses_1cc6e9e73ffe2HfOe2xPGj0ykX","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"apply_patch","callID":"call_YuGOnGrD236TSQa5CuGnBxDQ","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"patchText":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Add File: /__w/eval-ont-agent-go/eval-ont-agent-go/RESEARCH.md\n+## PMID:8321236 \"The fission yeast ferric reductase gene frp1+ is required for ferric iron uptake and encodes a protein that is homologous to the gp91-phox subunit of the human NADPH phagocyte oxidoreductase.\"\n+\n+Primary experimental paper identifying Frp1 as a cell-surface ferric reductase required for ferric iron uptake in fission yeast. This supports the existence of a ferric iron reductase activity distinct from siderophore-specific reductase activity.\n+\n+* SUPPORT: PMID:8321236 \"We have identified a cell surface ferric reductase activity in the fission yeast Schizosaccharomyces pombe. A mutant strain deficient in this activity was also deficient in ferric iron uptake, while ferrous iron uptake was not impaired.\"\n+    - Supports the biological activity of ferric iron reduction during reductive iron assimilation.\n+    - Supports use of a general ferric iron reductase term for Frp1-associated annotation.\n+\n+## PMID:34614242 \"Fission yeast RNA-binding proteins Puf2 and Puf4 are involved in repression of ferrireductase Frp1 expression in response to iron.\"\n+\n+Recent experimental support that Frp1 is a ferrireductase in S. pombe and part of the reductive iron uptake pathway.\n+\n+* SUPPORT: PMID:34614242 \"Cells expressing Puf2 and Puf4 stimulate decay of the frp1+ mRNA encoding a key enzyme of the reductive iron uptake pathway.\"\n+    - Supports the placement of Frp1 in reductive iron uptake biology.\n+    - Provides modern terminology linking Frp1 to ferrireductase activity.\n+\n+## PMID:39940646 \"The Ferroxidase-Permease System for Transport of Iron Across Membranes: From Yeast to Humans.\"\n+\n+Recent review covering yeast ferroxidase-permease systems and iron uptake context, useful for the broader definition provenance and issue rationale.\n+\n+* SUPPORT: PMID:39940646 \"Transport of iron across the cell membrane is a tightly controlled process carried out by specific proteins in all living cells. In yeast and in mammals, a system formed by an enzyme with ferroxidase activity coupled to a membrane transporter supports iron uptake or iron efflux, respectively.\"\n+    - Supports the broader reductive iron assimilation context motivating the requested term.\n+    - Serves as current review-level provenance for the activity branch context.\n+\n+## RHEA:71767\n+\n+The issue discussion identifies RHEA:71767 as the matching reaction for ferric iron reductase activity. The new term uses this as the reaction definition source and exact-match xref.\n*** Add File: /__w/eval-ont-agent-go/eval-ont-agent-go/DESIGN_PATTERNS.md\n+## Relevant pattern assessment for issue #27593\n+\n+No dedicated DOSDP appears to govern this molecular function reaction term.\n+\n+Relevant ontology precedent:\n+\n+- `GO:0008823` cupric reductase (NADH) activity\n+- `GO:0016152` mercury (II) reductase (NADP+) activity\n+- `GO:0047852` diferric-transferrin reductase (NAD+) activity\n+- `GO:0052851` ferric-chelate reductase (NADPH) activity\n+- `GO:0140618` ferric-chelate reductase (NADH) activity\n+\n+Observed pattern:\n+\n+- Molecular function reaction terms in this branch use a reaction-style text definition.\n+- The reaction source is typically a `RHEA` xref in the definition provenance and an exact-match `xref`.\n+- Parentage is typically `GO:0016723` when the acceptor is NAD or NADP.\n+- No `intersection_of` axioms are needed for this kind of term.\n+\n+Applied here:\n+\n+- New term `GO:7770068` follows the established reductase reaction-term pattern.\n+- `GO:0000293` is kept as the broader grouping term and reparented beneath the new ferric iron reductase activity term.\n+- The `GO:0000293` definition was broadened from siderophore-specific chelation to generic chelation to match the label and child terms.\n*** End Patch"},"output":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA RESEARCH.md\nA DESIGN_PATTERNS.md","metadata":{"diff":"Index: /__w/eval-ont-agent-go/eval-ont-agent-go/RESEARCH.md\n===================================================================\n--- /__w/eval-ont-agent-go/eval-ont-agent-go/RESEARCH.md\n+++ /__w/eval-ont-agent-go/eval-ont-agent-go/RESEARCH.md\n@@ -0,0 +1,27 @@\n+## PMID:8321236 \"The fission yeast ferric reductase gene frp1+ is required for ferric iron uptake and encodes a protein that is homologous to the gp91-phox subunit of the human NADPH phagocyte oxidoreductase.\"\n+\n+Primary experimental paper identifying Frp1 as a cell-surface ferric reductase required for ferric iron uptake in fission yeast. This supports the existence of a ferric iron reductase activity distinct from siderophore-specific reductase activity.\n+\n+* SUPPORT: PMID:8321236 \"We have identified a cell surface ferric reductase activity in the fission yeast Schizosaccharomyces pombe. A mutant strain deficient in this activity was also deficient in ferric iron uptake, while ferrous iron uptake was not impaired.\"\n+    - Supports the biological activity of ferric iron reduction during reductive iron assimilation.\n+    - Supports use of a general ferric iron reductase term for Frp1-associated annotation.\n+\n+## PMID:34614242 \"Fission yeast RNA-binding proteins Puf2 and Puf4 are involved in repression of ferrireductase Frp1 expression in response to iron.\"\n+\n+Recent experimental support that Frp1 is a ferrireductase in S. pombe and part of the reductive iron uptake pathway.\n+\n+* SUPPORT: PMID:34614242 \"Cells expressing Puf2 and Puf4 stimulate decay of the frp1+ mRNA encoding a key enzyme of the reductive iron uptake pathway.\"\n+    - Supports the placement of Frp1 in reductive iron uptake biology.\n+    - Provides modern terminology linking Frp1 to ferrireductase activity.\n+\n+## PMID:39940646 \"The Ferroxidase-Permease System for Transport of Iron Across Membranes: From Yeast to Humans.\"\n+\n+Recent review covering yeast ferroxidase-permease systems and iron uptake context, useful for the broader definition provenance and issue rationale.\n+\n+* SUPPORT: PMID:39940646 \"Transport of iron across the cell membrane is a tightly controlled process carried out by specific proteins in all living cells. In yeast and in mammals, a system formed by an enzyme with ferroxidase activity coupled to a membrane transporter supports iron uptake or iron efflux, respectively.\"\n+    - Supports the broader reductive iron assimilation context motivating the requested term.\n+    - Serves as current review-level provenance for the activity branch context.\n+\n+## RHEA:71767\n+\n+The issue discussion identifies RHEA:71767 as the matching reaction for ferric iron reductase activity. The new term uses this as the reaction definition source and exact-match xref.\n\nIndex: /__w/eval-ont-agent-go/eval-ont-agent-go/DESIGN_PATTERNS.md\n===================================================================\n--- /__w/eval-ont-agent-go/eval-ont-agent-go/DESIGN_PATTERNS.md\n+++ /__w/eval-ont-agent-go/eval-ont-agent-go/DESIGN_PATTERNS.md\n@@ -0,0 +1,24 @@\n+## Relevant pattern assessment for issue #27593\n+\n+No dedicated DOSDP appears to govern this molecular function reaction term.\n+\n+Relevant ontology precedent:\n+\n+- `GO:0008823` cupric reductase (NADH) activity\n+- `GO:0016152` mercury (II) reductase (NADP+) activity\n+- `GO:0047852` diferric-transferrin reductase (NAD+) activity\n+- `GO:0052851` ferric-chelate reductase (NADPH) activity\n+- `GO:0140618` ferric-chelate reductase (NADH) activity\n+\n+Observed pattern:\n+\n+- Molecular function reaction terms in this branch use a reaction-style text definition.\n+- The reaction source is typically a `RHEA` xref in the definition provenance and an exact-match `xref`.\n+- Parentage is typically `GO:0016723` when the acceptor is NAD or NADP.\n+- No `intersection_of` axioms are needed for this kind of term.\n+\n+Applied here:\n+\n+- New term `GO:7770068` follows the established reductase reaction-term pattern.\n+- `GO:0000293` is kept as the broader grouping term and reparented beneath the new ferric iron reductase activity term.\n+- The `GO:0000293` definition was broadened from siderophore-specific chelation to generic chelation to match the label and child terms.\n\n","files":[{"filePath":"/__w/eval-ont-agent-go/eval-ont-agent-go/RESEARCH.md","relativePath":"RESEARCH.md","type":"add","patch":"Index: /__w/eval-ont-agent-go/eval-ont-agent-go/RESEARCH.md\n===================================================================\n--- /__w/eval-ont-agent-go/eval-ont-agent-go/RESEARCH.md\n+++ /__w/eval-ont-agent-go/eval-ont-agent-go/RESEARCH.md\n@@ -0,0 +1,27 @@\n+## PMID:8321236 \"The fission yeast ferric reductase gene frp1+ is required for ferric iron uptake and encodes a protein that is homologous to the gp91-phox subunit of the human NADPH phagocyte oxidoreductase.\"\n+\n+Primary experimental paper identifying Frp1 as a cell-surface ferric reductase required for ferric iron uptake in fission yeast. This supports the existence of a ferric iron reductase activity distinct from siderophore-specific reductase activity.\n+\n+* SUPPORT: PMID:8321236 \"We have identified a cell surface ferric reductase activity in the fission yeast Schizosaccharomyces pombe. A mutant strain deficient in this activity was also deficient in ferric iron uptake, while ferrous iron uptake was not impaired.\"\n+    - Supports the biological activity of ferric iron reduction during reductive iron assimilation.\n+    - Supports use of a general ferric iron reductase term for Frp1-associated annotation.\n+\n+## PMID:34614242 \"Fission yeast RNA-binding proteins Puf2 and Puf4 are involved in repression of ferrireductase Frp1 expression in response to iron.\"\n+\n+Recent experimental support that Frp1 is a ferrireductase in S. p